From AIDS, non-communicable diseases in eight fundamental points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes and chronic respiratory diseases, account for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, physical inactivity, poor diet and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet despite widespread knowledge of the risks, obesity on a global scale is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It is within this context that networks of alliances for non-communicable diseases met from December 9 to 11 at the second World Forum of the Alliance on Non-Communicable Diseases in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions aimed at regulating NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the AIDS fight movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to carry out interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress achieved.
While the battle is not over, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against NCDs can turn back this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the NCD community as being in need of "an electric shock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
As global attention focuses on preventing NCDs, those seeking to control preventable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC of AIDS-fighting organizations.
The first letter that the NCD community must take into account is "A," for activism.
Any person over 40 surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-ins" during scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets and even shut down the Food and Drug Administration headquarters for a day in October 1988.
Globally, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the NCD community must adopt a more daring approach to budgets - the "B" of the AIDS-fighting movement's strategy.
Civic organizations and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires money.
The AIDS-fighting movement was clear about this from the beginning and pressured for resources to effectively support its awareness and empowerment activities.
« C » represents coalitions: the AIDS-fighting movements quickly realized that progress comes only with multiple supports.
Activists have linked people living with HIV to those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from the public sector in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS-fighting movement also understood that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential to the spread of its support.
Thus, "D," the determining factor of success, consisted of "drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge."
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make smart decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a driving role in the AIDS crisis.
NCDs are no less isolated in their causality and also undergo a multisectoral approach to prevention.
The commitment - "E" - was what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which championed the mantra "Nothing about us without us," AIDS advocates demanded the representation of existing organizations to address the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Board of Directors reserved for representatives of civil society.
This norm is so deeply ingrained in the AIDS fight movement that it would almost be unthinkable for an AIDS meeting to take place without representation from the community.
Disease prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives and "F" - framing the issue - is essential for the AIDS community to gain the support of political leaders.
In particular, access to AIDS treatments has been presented as a matter of economic justice.
Framing the narrative this way leads to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the extent that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
An equally important framing of the issue for AIDS, a highly relevant question for the NCD movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to place more emphasis on people's lifestyle choices, rather than attributing state responsibility for healthcare provision and the elimination of legal discrimination.
In the AIDS debate, gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a "gay disease" and gender identity became embedded in the DNA of the AIDS movement from the beginning.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to examine how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Gender, therefore, must become a focal point of NCD prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" - human rights - are the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in the workplace, in schools, and in medical centers.
Strategic litigation has ensured equality under the law.
The AIDS movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The NCD movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods to children.
We could continue listing the lessons learned from the fight against AIDS all the way through the alphabet, but we feel it is appropriate to conclude with "H," since human rights provided the response to AIDS and should provide the response to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same is true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The NCD and AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
